				<outline text="Introducing opmlToJs -- an NPM package" created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:38:01 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="As I &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2017/08/06.html#a122101&quot;&gt;reported&lt;/a&gt; yesterday I have been modularizing my Node work by creating packages of reusable code. The first one I want to show you is called &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/opmlToJs&quot;&gt;opmlToJs&lt;/a&gt;. It does two things well:" created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:38:50 GMT" flNumberedSubs="true">
						<outline text="Parses an OPML string and turns it into a JavaScript object." created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:39:06 GMT"/>
						<outline text="Takes one of those objects and turns it turns it back into an OPML string." created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:39:21 GMT"/>
						</outline>
					<outline text="The JSON object it produces is set up the way all my outline-processing tools in JavaScript expect them, so it works with the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/outlineBrowser&quot;&gt;outlineBrowser&lt;/a&gt; toolkit and many others." created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:40:03 GMT"/>
					<outline text="If you have to consume OPML or generate it, &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/opmlToJs&quot;&gt;opmlToJs&lt;/a&gt; makes it easy." created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:42:18 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&quot;OPML&quot; is a standard XML-based file format used for outlines, presentations and lists for RSS feed readers. &quot;River5&quot; uses OPML to import and export feed lists. &quot;Fargo&quot; and &quot;Little Outliner&quot; use OPML as the file format. OPML has been around &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/davenet/2000/09/24/opml10.html&quot;&gt;since&lt;/a&gt; 2000." created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:45:14 GMT"/>
					<outline text="If you have any questions or suggestions, please post an &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/opmlToJs/issues&quot;&gt;issue&lt;/a&gt; on the GitHub project. " created="Mon, 07 Aug 2017 13:44:13 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 6" created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 14:35:39 GMT" name="06">
				<outline text="I've been modularizing my &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/&quot;&gt;Node&lt;/a&gt; work using &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Npm_(software)&quot;&gt;NPM packages&lt;/a&gt;. Murphy-willing I'm going to be writing each of them up, in turn, &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2017/08/&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; on Scripting News. You'll recognize the functionality as the kind of stuff you need to build DaveLand on the Internets in Node. The first one up is a really good OPML-to-and-from-JavaScript package. Naturally this stuff will mostly be of interest to developers and people who might want to become one." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 16:21:01 GMT" type="outline" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/06/wonderWoman.png"/>
				<outline text="The way you know podcasting isn't dominated by anyone is at the end of every podcast. There is no single place to go to hear a podcast. (This is in response to a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-31/spotify-is-coming-after-apple-with-a-new-podcast-initiative&quot;&gt;Bloomberg piece&lt;/a&gt; that said among other things that Apple dominates podcasting and Spotify is going to challenge them, which I say is nuts.)" created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 16:53:34 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I did a &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2017/08/06/appleDoesNotDominatePodcasts.m4a&quot;&gt;voice memo&lt;/a&gt; for Rex about Apple and podcast &quot;dominance.&quot;" created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 23:48:50 GMT" type="outline" enclosure="http://scripting.com/2017/08/06/appleDoesNotDominatePodcasts.m4a" enclosureType="audio/mpeg" enclosureLength="4293925"/>
				<outline text="I know this is unfashionable for someone with my values and friendships, but maybe the people who blame the press for the mess have a point." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 19:48:56 GMT" type="tweet" tweetId="894284218859233280" tweetUserName="davewiner"/>
				<outline text="Watched a bit of &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Sharpton&quot;&gt;Al Sharpton&lt;/a&gt; today. He said Trump is of NYC in 80s and 90s. As of course was Sharpton. Sure he knows a lot about Trump." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 18:17:40 GMT" type="tweet" tweetId="894261630795751424" tweetUserName="davewiner"/>
				<outline text="I think people want to &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/894240743166025728&quot;&gt;forget&lt;/a&gt; that the US has stage 4 cancer. It's spreading to our bones. Whether we come back is in question" created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 18:21:17 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="If you can write a stinging editorial putting down a class of people, balance it with an example of someone in that class being good." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:49:34 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="If a million people &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/894204096516894720&quot;&gt;say&lt;/a&gt; someone is wrong, my instinct is to find what's right." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 14:35:40 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="If you &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/894237830473535488&quot;&gt;fight&lt;/a&gt; for free speech only for people who agree with you then you are not for free speech." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 16:46:19 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Remind me to tell you the tale of goatfuck.js." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 16:47:20 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="A lot of the hype about Node.js is bullshit" created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:51:40 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I think &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.w3schools.com/&quot;&gt;w3schools&lt;/a&gt; does a good job. I use their stuff as a reference all the time for net programming. I was looking at their new &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/&quot;&gt;tutorial&lt;/a&gt; for Node.js and on the first page they repeat the hype about Node that I've always suspected was BS, and now that I have a few years in, I know it is. " created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:51:49 GMT" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/06/hippieBus.png"/>
					<outline text="Node is a fine environment, I use it as my main server runtime, and lately I've been &lt;a href=&quot;http://this.how/electricRiver/&quot;&gt;building&lt;/a&gt; a lot with &lt;a href=&quot;https://electron.atom.io/&quot;&gt;Electron&lt;/a&gt;, and there you're using Node on the desktop. I have a love-hate relationship with Node, I'm a prisoner to some bad design imho but it's great to have one syntax instead of two for client and server apps. " created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:52:52 GMT"/>
					<outline text="But other environments like Java and Python are probably just as efficient as Node &lt;i&gt;without all the crazy callbacks. &lt;/i&gt;Their runtimes can suspend a process until its I/O completes. All the other languages/environments do that. It is not something that only Node does. " created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:54:24 GMT"/>
					<outline text="And Node is not single-threaded! You have many threads. A single-threaded server runtime is impossible. That's one of the reasons I strongly suspected all the hype when I was new to Node." created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:55:13 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The difference between Node and other environments is that the others hide the suspending and resuming of your app behind an abstraction layer, &lt;i&gt;and that's good, &lt;/i&gt;that makes your code &lt;i&gt;much&lt;/i&gt; simpler. In every way imho the way JavaScript does I/O is a major step backwards. But like I said I love/hate JS. I've &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stockholm_syndrome&quot;&gt;made my peace&lt;/a&gt; with the &lt;a href=&quot;http://callbackhell.com/&quot;&gt;way&lt;/a&gt; I/O works in Node. :peach:" created="Sun, 06 Aug 2017 17:55:54 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 5" created="Sat, 05 Aug 2017 15:14:38 GMT" name="05">
				<outline text="If you're reading RSS and Atom feeds in Node apps, you need &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/danmactough/node-feedparser&quot;&gt;feedparser&lt;/a&gt;, written by my friend Dan MacTough. I've been using his code in my own &quot;River5&quot; for years. It's solid and dependable. As a gesture of gratitude I published &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/feedParserDemo&quot;&gt;example code&lt;/a&gt; yesterday that helps you get started with feedparser. " created="Sat, 05 Aug 2017 15:14:39 GMT" type="outline" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/05/loveRss.png"/>
				<outline text="&quot;You can fake caring but you can't fake showing up.&quot; Not sure said &lt;a href=&quot;https://duckduckgo.com/?q=You+can+fake+caring+but+you+can%27t+fake+showing+up&amp;t=hq&amp;ia=web&quot;&gt;this&lt;/a&gt;, but it's an important idea. " created="Sat, 05 Aug 2017 15:27:02 GMT" type="tweet" tweetId="893856534853279744" tweetUserName="davewiner"/>
