				<outline text="I post too much &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/TheComedyHumor/status/893510547420983296&quot;&gt;Twitter stuff&lt;/a&gt; to my blog. I know it. " created="Sat, 05 Aug 2017 18:38:28 GMT" type="outline" urlTweet="https://twitter.com/TheComedyHumor/status/893510547420983296"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 4" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 13:26:11 GMT" name="04">
				<outline text="Good morning beer drinkers! :beer: " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 13:26:12 GMT" type="outline" urltweet="https://twitter.com/BFI/status/893418749822255108"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/NYCWater/status/893569853545734148&quot;&gt;Summer Streets&lt;/a&gt; is tomorrow. Park Ave is open to bike riders &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Park+Ave+%26+E+72nd+St,+New+York,+NY+10021/Brooklyn+Bridge,+New+York,+NY+10038/@40.7386761,-74.0200266,13z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m14!4m13!1m5!1m1!1s0x89c258eb3f6868c5:0x2112eb436b9cf240!2m2!1d-73.9639279!2d40.7711473!1m5!1m1!1s0x89c25a2343ce7b2b:0x2526ddba7abd465c!2m2!1d-73.9968643!2d40.7060855!3e2&quot;&gt;from&lt;/a&gt; 72nd down to the Brooklyn Bridge. It's a treat to experience the city largely without cars on three Saturdays in August. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 21:00:04 GMT" type="outline" urlTweet="https://twitter.com/NYCWater/status/893569853545734148"/>
				<outline text="Einstein and his &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/HistoryInPix/status/893605218226769920&quot;&gt;therapist&lt;/a&gt;.  " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 23:01:31 GMT" type="outline" urlTweet="https://twitter.com/HistoryInPix/status/893605218226769920"/>
				<outline text="Probably &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chronology_of_Soviet_secret_police_agencies&quot;&gt;Russian&lt;/a&gt; secret police wanted &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.secretservice.gov/&quot;&gt;Secret Service&lt;/a&gt; out of &lt;a href=&quot;http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/08/secret-service-exits-trump-tower-over-lease-dispute-report.html&quot;&gt;Trump Tower&lt;/a&gt;." created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 16:23:34 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="The next episode of Game of Thrones has &lt;a href=&quot;http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/game-of-thrones-episode-leak-online-hbo-hack-1202515776/&quot;&gt;leaked&lt;/a&gt;. Here's a &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/893504022920998912&quot;&gt;poll&lt;/a&gt; that asks if you would watch it tonight or wait until Sunday. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 16:09:08 GMT" type="outline" urlTweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/893504022920998912"/>
				<outline text="Hooking up to a user's S3 bucket for output" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:19:50 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="Suppose I wanted to add a feature to one of my Electron apps that allowed a user to hook it up to an S3 location that they own and pay for. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:19:59 GMT"/>
					<outline text="What's the best way to provide access?" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:28:33 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I imagine that's what &lt;a href=&quot;https://aws.amazon.com/iam/&quot;&gt;IAM&lt;/a&gt; is for. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:28:41 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I need to dig in. If you know of any easy howto's please &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/Scripting-News/issues/19&quot;&gt;post a note here&lt;/a&gt;. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:28:55 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Also just revisited their &lt;a href=&quot;https://aws.amazon.com/documentation/efs/&quot;&gt;Elastic Filesystem&lt;/a&gt; docs and they seem to have come a long way since the last time I looked. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:29:08 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Feedparser sample code" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:01:34 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="TL;DR: New &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/feedParserDemo/blob/master/demo.js&quot;&gt;sample code&lt;/a&gt; for getting started with feed parsing in Node. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:02:03 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I use the &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/danmactough/node-feedparser&quot;&gt;feedparser&lt;/a&gt; package in &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/river5&quot;&gt;River5&lt;/a&gt;. So all my news flows through this code. That's a lot of news, and it's been working solidly for years." created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:01:40 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Back in 2013 when I was getting started on Node, it was a little tricky adapting to feedparser, because the package is designed for maximum efficiency at the expense of a bit of ease-of-use, especially for a Node newbie. "/>
					<outline text="In the spirit of giving back to a product I use a lot, I pulled out a bit of &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/reader/blob/master/davereader.js#L555&quot;&gt;code&lt;/a&gt; from River5 and simplified it so it makes a &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/scripting/feedParserDemo/blob/master/demo.js&quot;&gt;good demo&lt;/a&gt; of feedparser. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:04:41 GMT"/>
					<outline text="If you're new to feedparser, this might help you get started a bit faster with less head-scratching. :beer:" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 18:05:05 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="If only CSS was better" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:52:19 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I was reading a bit about the &lt;a href=&quot;https://duckduckgo.com/?q=why+css+sucks&amp;t=hu&amp;ia=web&quot;&gt;history&lt;/a&gt; of CSS, and kept thinking -- what a shame, they did it totally backwards. This is what I would have done. First I would have made a design tool that worked really well. Then I'd have it spit out XML (sorry JSON didn't exist at the time) and teach the browser to render that. All this would happen iteratively. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:53:16 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The priorities would be:" created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:47:16 GMT" flNumberedSubs="true">
						<outline text="Leverages the talents of designers." created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:48:29 GMT"/>
						<outline text="Good performance in the browser and on the net (considerations: how long to render, how big the files are, latency, bandwidth, out over time)." created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:48:53 GMT"/>
						<outline text="Elegance of the format used to communicate the design to the browser." created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:49:32 GMT"/>
						</outline>
					<outline text="The third item is way way down the list. Yes it should be easy to do it by hand. But we shouldn't &lt;i&gt;always&lt;/i&gt; be doing it by hand as it works now. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:54:23 GMT"/>
					<outline text="What we ended up using was impossible to create a tool for, is utterly perplexing to everyone who has to use it, and is missing huge features that cripple everything we do. The &lt;i&gt;whole world&lt;/i&gt; is now built around the crazy design system called CSS. Everywhere and everything." created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:49:59 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Also I have to say we were working on exactly this at &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/dwiner/outlinersProgramming.html&quot;&gt;Living Videotext&lt;/a&gt; in 1986 and 1987. Had done a lot of prototyping. It was rules-based and you could see the impact of your rules immediately on the screen. Made iteration fast. Would have been perfect for responsive design. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 15:50:59 GMT"/>
					<outline text="It's one of those &quot;if only&quot; things -- if only we had been in position to do this, in a competitive way. That's one of the big tradeoffs of going the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.w3.org/Consortium/activities&quot;&gt;standards&lt;/a&gt; route. You often get really bad designs and have to live with their limits, for a generation or two. " created="Fri, 04 Aug 2017 16:01:05 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 3" created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 11:37:40 GMT" name="03">
				<outline text="Thinking about &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_F._Kelly&quot;&gt;General Kelly&lt;/a&gt; today. Assumption -- he's an honorable person. He's also now inside at the White House. There isn't anything that's secret from the &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_House_Chief_of_Staff&quot;&gt;Chief of Staff&lt;/a&gt;. So how long before the complete picture of the criminality of this White House is revealed to him? Hard to believe it hasn't already happened. So if he's honorable, he has to come clean, make a statement to the special prosecutor and ask for instructions. If not that, is there a backroom deal? Can't imagine there is. Who would want to make one if they didn't have to. Priebus was a clown, in way over his head. Kelly has had a chance to watch it from the Cabinet and he chose to go in. Puzzling." created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 18:03:53 GMT" type="outline" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/03/trumpHead.png"/>
				<outline text="When smart phones are really smart they will text you when something bad is about to happen." created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 11:40:42 GMT" type="outline" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/893067465256828928"/>
				<outline text="The great thing about open source software is that if you want a feature and it's hard to explain you can just do it.  " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 11:39:46 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Had a thought that this year instead of picking a blogger of the year, I might do something different. Like write a survey of the State of the Blog. I should have been doing that all along, really. As blogs got chopped up and turned into corners of huge multi-billion dollar tech empires. So much so that there's almost nothing left. But it's not nothing. So taking an annual inventory probably isn't a bad idea. " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:44:29 GMT" type="outline" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/03/alice.png"/>
				<outline text="Dropbox update" created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:40:28 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="When I wrote about my woes with Dropbox yesterday, they were just getting started. " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:40:35 GMT" xref="http://scripting.com/2017/08/02.html#a081737" image="http://scripting.com/images/2017/08/02/bigGulp.png"/>
					<outline text="The rainbow cursors were back in force. Then something happened. The fog lifted. I remembered, the whole reason I moved my Dropbox off the internal drive is that the internal drive is broken. I had forgotten to leave myself a note to that effect. " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:46:58 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I had a La Cie 1TB external &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00VMEXGJ0/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&amp;psc=1&quot;&gt;Firewire drive&lt;/a&gt; I wasn't using. I'm now using it for Dropbox. Hopefully it will be quieter and faster than the drive I was using before. Whatever. As long as it works! " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:47:25 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Anyway, even though I was offline with Dropbox, that truly is an important net connectivity thing these days, I got a lot of good software &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2013/08/28/programmingPhilosophyModularize&quot;&gt;factoring&lt;/a&gt; and building done. " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:42:20 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I have been building with &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/foreverjs/forever&quot;&gt;Forever&lt;/a&gt; as my starting point. I want i to do more for me. It's getting there. And I have factored my Electron functionality so that it can be used in other projects. That's where I'm headed with &quot;Instant Dave&quot;." created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 15:42:56 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Dropbox slowdown continues" created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 11:37:41 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I'm writing this at 7:30AM but have no idea when it will apear on my blog. " created="Thu, 03 Aug 2017 11:37:50 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 2" created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:17:36 GMT" name="02">
				<outline text="There may be enough people who agree the net should have lasting structures free of tech business models that the problem could be solved. " created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 14:45:58 GMT" type="outline" xref="http://scripting.com/2017/08/01.html#a085611"/>
				<outline text="I have a huge Dropbox. " created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:17:37 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I have a huge Dropbox. Actually two. One for my servers and one for me personally. I pay $99 per year for each. No way to avoid it. Each has a 1TB limit, but actually use less than 100GB. The servers update files a lot, so there's lots of traffic on my Dropbox account. I don't begrudge them $200 a year. They provide a lot of service for the money." created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:20:03 GMT" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/02/bigGulp.png"/>
					<outline text="In early May I reprovisioned my desktop Mac because the machine was performing badly, and I couldn't figure why. So I bought a 5TB external drive, and put everything vital on it, including my Dropbox folder. That was probably a mistake. Because you can hear that drive doing its thing all the time night and day. And then the machine started getting slow. Again. Rainbow cursors. Just like the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vY60vzAWqxw&quot;&gt;Mac ad&lt;/a&gt; that shows the PC going to &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neverland&quot;&gt;Never-Land&lt;/a&gt;, except it's my Mac that's doing it. Programming or writing under these circumstances is like having random &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=senior%20moment&quot;&gt;Senior Moments&lt;/a&gt;, which I unfortunately now have for real (I'm 62). A random computer-induced Senior Moment. Ugh. Just what I need! (Not.)" created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:20:15 GMT"/>
					<outline text="So on Monday morning I decided it was time to move my Dropbox folder from the external drive to my unused 1TB internal drive. First there was a permissions problem. Fixed that. Then it took a good 24 hours to move the folder! All the while the computer was unusable. So I used my laptop and surprisingly got a lot of good work done. I should probably go on a trip. Anyway.." created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:24:02 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Now everything's done, but Dropbox is downloading the whole folder again, for what reason exactly? As of last night it had over 600K files to download. This morning when I start work it's still got &lt;a href=&quot;http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/02/dropboxSync.png&quot;&gt;over 400K&lt;/a&gt;. What the fuck Dropbox. What was the point of taking 24 hours to move the folder if you just have to re-download everything all over again?" created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:25:28 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Anyway, one of the advantages of being a senior is that I will forget all this soon enough. And because I'm a senior, I'm laughing out loud while I write this. Cackling really. This is what happens when you get old. Your mind and body fall apart but your sense of humor gets really sharp! God is merciful. Also the programming project I'm working on is truly wonderful. Open source software makes all kinds of things possible. " created="Wed, 02 Aug 2017 12:26:43 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 1" created="Tue, 01 Aug 2017 12:50:04 GMT" name="01">
				<outline text="Welcome to the &lt;i&gt;new month&lt;/i&gt; of August 2017! :rocket: " created="Tue, 01 Aug 2017 12:50:05 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I never pass on links to autoplay pages. I don't care how great the story is." created="Tue, 01 Aug 2017 17:41:14 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="The &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/nickfthilton/status/892347108149383172&quot;&gt;trailer&lt;/a&gt; for Sharknado 5 looks pretty great. " created="Tue, 01 Aug 2017 15:44:16 GMT" type="outline" urltweet="https://twitter.com/nickfthilton/status/892347108149383172"/>
				<outline text="There's &lt;a href=&quot;http://pitchfork.com/thepitch/the-soundcloud-you-loved-is-doomed/&quot;&gt;more&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7881154/soundcloud-trouble-layoffs-sale-acquisition&quot;&gt;talk&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/01/magazine/if-soundcloud-disappears-what-happens-to-its-music-culture.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss&quot;&gt;about&lt;/a&gt; SoundCloud failing, or &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-29/soundcloud-is-said-near-deal-to-sell-stakes-to-private-equity&quot;&gt;changing&lt;/a&gt; radically. Which raises again the basic question behind creative work on the Internet -- when are we going to start building structures designed for longevity. With an economic model other than founders-get-rich. We should be thinking about a creative environment that builds on its achievements, and creates a usable archive. " created="Tue, 01 Aug 2017 12:56:11 GMT" type="outline" image="http:///scripting.com/images/2017/08/01/tree.png"/>
				</outline>
			</outline>
